@taraszkab remix is out!!!! Please go show some love. Go through page or @iamisaacwheadon  to get access to it. I gave me the opportunity to not only create on of his album art for a track that will be coming out soon but also this video edit for this remix.  This man here has been working on a journey through music but also as a person. He got me my first book and from there I been reading here and there, but I'm grateful he started this. The first time we had a meeting for a cover art we never even talked about the actual work. We had a deep talk about life and the journey we both have with our form of art. Through him I met @iamisaacwheadon and I'm lucky well not really like @iamisaacwheadon said its not a coincidence it was meant to happen. But I been a spectator to his journey and I can't wait to see all that music you have stored. Also I went to show some love on his first jiu jitsu tournament. He won first place on both competition and the first one was from a armbar!!!! Then this guy does me the honor to have his first place medal which I still have hanging with pride. Thank for everything and can't wait for more music. Please go support!! Go show some love to our own !! ⚡🖤

Starting my day with my own tea in a Giada to go cup 😄 First, @giadadelaurentiis is my favorite chef! I plan to definitely come back to @prontobygiada today for some real food 😄 Second, today is the @mgma_ Lean Six Sigma White Belt Program, the first of several programs that certify in process improvement. I’m taking this program for career development. 
So what is process improvement? Essentially, when your working in an organization with daily processes, the goal is efficiency. Sometimes that doesn’t happen right away. There’s changes that need to be made. However, how do you know which change to make, then how and when to make those changes? What if a change doesn’t work? This is the process improvement cycle. 
I’m ready to dive in, learn it, and become a certified White Belt! 
Did you watch my #IGLive? 💁🏻‍♀️

'Tala', colorway 'Mobesk' in wool with silk accents as a possible design for this southern California home. Tala is one of the ancient traditional rhythmic patterns of stressed and unstressed beats played on a percussion instrument in South Asia. The pattern for 'Tala' is derived from an image of rare ice balls that formed in Lake Michigan and floated to Chicago's shore this winter. A rare phenomenon dependent on extreme cold, wind, and small pieces of ice continuously rolling along the top of the lake. For myself the pattern when abstracted has an interesting non symmetrical rhythm that reminds me of the experimental composer John Cage's prepared piano works. A similar sound found in the traditional music of South Asia. Finding that jumping off point to develop a concept is always intriguing. I am always interested in how designers and artists think. How they extrapolate more tangible ideas from abstract perceptions, sometimes based on pure form and feeling, and then design functioning products that expresses those perceptions.
.

色々手続き済ませて
搭乗案内待つスペースには
寝っ転がれるソファーがあるから
そこで家族3人でゴロゴロ。
たいちゃんも機内入ると動けなくなるから、
ソファの上で思う存分遊ばせた⭐️
いざ搭乗😊
バシネット席頼んでおいたので
足のスペースが広い✨
子供いる人は
バシネット使うにしろ使わないにしろ
バシネット席のスペース広いから
おすすめ☆
離陸するときの耳抜きは
おっぱい吸わせて
特に問題なし⭐️
離陸してまもなく
周りが睡眠体勢に.....😅
みんなに鳴き声で 
迷惑かけないようにっと
必死でおっぱいで寝かしつけ😭
無事腕の中で就寝、、、
バシネット用意してくれたから
バシネットに置こうとトライするも
失敗&腕の中でもアナウンスとかの音で
なかなか深い眠りにならず
寝かしつけに必死になる母😭
朝ごはんの時間🍴
たいちゃんの機内食は
キューピーのベビーフード
3個も❤︎❤︎❤︎
着陸態勢に入ったら
耳抜きのため
おっぱい吸わせる😊
特に問題なく耳抜きクリア⭐️
結局ずっと母の腕の中で過ごしたから、
母睡眠不足&身体中痛い😭が、
ハワイの景色見てすぐ回復❤️
行きの飛行機は
こんな感じでした✈️✈️✈️

Anchorage carries on at edge of the world
.
I’ve always enjoyed how the frailties of the human-engineered world are made so bare here. It’s all so new, the roads and planes and skyscrapers, the grocery stores and baseball fields. A hundred years ago there was none of this. It was a forest and creeks, beaches and bears. Dena’ina crossing it back and forth for food and family
.
In a way it’s no different than anywhere else in this modern world, where our center of gravity is always out ahead of us somewhere as we race for the horizon. But here, the horizons are so much closer. I run out my door and reach the end of the road in a few minutes. Then it’s beach’s and mud and mountain. Volcanoes and salmon and strong people in tiny villages surrounded by forest and tundra
.
I’v always liked to know where the exit is, and it’s comforting to have so many here. I left the city yesterday. I climbed down off of the paved path and onto the beach. There were cranes and seagulls. I scanned for belugas. I learned the shape of Mount Susitna and the Alaska Range
.
.
.
.
.
.
